You can count on snack mix to be the first thing to disappear at a party. Salty, cheesy, crunchy (and with an optional kick of heat)¬óthis addicting combo is a flavor-packed blend of popcorn, tortilla chips, and corn nuts gently scented with tangy barbecue sauce and Spanish smoked paprika. It's the perfect savory balance to an evening's worth of Halloween sweets.
  
  Editor's Note:   This recipe is part of  Gourmet's  Modern Menu for Halloween: Spooky Snacks. Menu also includes  Mozzarella and Roasted Red Pepper Boo-schetta 
 and  Chocolate-Covered Pumpkin Cheesecake Pops.

items.dek:
The killer combination of coconut, almonds, and milk chocolate makes for a delectable candy bar.  One of the most iconic of American candies, the Almond Joy, is famous for its creamy coconut filling topped with almonds and covered in milk chocolate. Its sibling, the Mounds bar, has the same coconut center but no almonds. Although the recipes for these two candies are top secret, it's possible to make wonderfully coconutty chocolate candies in your own home. 

  History:  The Almond Joy was invented in 1946 by the Peter Paul Candy Manufacturing Company in Connecticut. The Mounds bar was the original version of the candy, premiering in 1921. Peter Paul used the unusual strategy of creating two very similar candies and advertising them as competing versions, encouraging consumers to pick a favorite. This tactic worked: Almond Joy and Mounds became two of the best-selling candies in the 1920s.  

  Serving Suggestions:  Trick-or-treaters will be delighted to find these candies in the Halloween candy bag. Wrap them in foil or place them in candy cups.  

  Candy-Making Notes:  You can eliminate the almonds and cover the coconut centers with dark chocolate. Better yet, make both versions and give your guests a pleasant dilemna of which to choose.

items.dek:
It seems na√Øve to talk about building a business on a single muffin, but in case of this pumpkin muffin, it's the truth. Instead of the heavy, dark-brown pumpkin muffins people expected, we offered them a light-textured, attractive, pastel orange mini-cake, sprinkled with sunflower seeds. Word about my baking spread, thanks to the success of those muffins. Thank you, Peggy Cullen, for sharing these beauties.
  

Bakers Note: If you use generous scoops of batter, the yield will be 12 muffins. For smaller muffins, use 7 muffin cups in each of 2 muffin pans. Distribute the batter in a random pattern (not in rows) in each pan so the muffins bake evenly. Butter only the cups that you are going to use, or the butter in the empty cups will burn.

items.caption: Truth-telling time: this honeycomb candy doesn't actually contain any honey. But it's crunchy and cool-looking and dipped in chocolate, so who cares?
Too often, white chocolate doesn't get invited to the party. But when it's paired with matcha (green-tea powder), white chocolate becomes the guest nobody wants to leave.
Rosewater is traditional in these notorious treats, but feel free to a different extract‚Äîorange, maybe, or vanilla.
This popcorn combines the sweetness of caramel with savory, salty nuts.  For a party favor, the cones are totally necessary.
Salted caramel marshmallows are a kind of exotic guest‚Äîa little bit mysterious, and totally seductive.
Press this festive, chewy nougat between 2 sheets of edible rice paper to create a polished look (and an easy-to-carry wrapper).
What would an over-the-top host do? Sprinkle these cookies with snacks he knows his guests enjoy. Popcorn for the adults, perhaps; M&Ms for the kids.
Airy marshmallow. Crispy bacon. This isn't the party favor‚Äîthis is the party itself.
Even if you have butter fingers, you can pull off these chocolate-covered Butterfinger candy treats. (Sorry, we had to.)
Caramel, chocolate, and salt bring down the house. Wrap individually to make these ready for the party guest bag.
Giving out bagged candy: lame. Giving out DIY candy: pro move.
Just imagine how these might taste melting away in a steaming mug of hot chocolate.
Don't skip the pecans‚Äîthey're what save these pralines (any praline, really) from being cloying.
Overachieving hosts, take note: If you make these, nobody will ever top you. (You'll have a hard time saying goodbye to that raspberry-rose buttercream, though.)

items.caption: Don't let the good looks of this eight-layer beauty fool you. It's easy to make. Toasted coconut is a knockout garnish that's also forgiving‚Äîit'll mask a less-than-perfect frosting job.

items.title: Chocolate Mayonnaise Cake
items.caption: Mayo in cake? Hold your judgement until you try this one. The mayonnaise gives it an incredibly moist and tender texture.

items.title: The Tomboy Cake
items.caption: Inspired by a style of cake from California's Miette bakeries, we frost the top and middle layers of this stunner but leave the sides naked to showcase the almond cake.

items.title: Caramel Cake
items.caption: If you're up to the challenge, this is a truly a fun cake. The perfect salty caramel icing, with its burnt-sugar crispiness, dissolves almost instantly on your tongue. Almost takes the sting out of getting older.

items.title: The Pink Cake
items.caption: Buttercream frosting is tinted pink by a raspberry puree for this super fun and extra rich chocolate cake.

items.title: Yellow Layer Cake with Chocolate-Sour Cream Frosting
items.caption: Forget the boxed version you grew up with. This yellow cake gets a rich dark-chocolate frosting with a touch of tang thanks to sour cream.

items.title: Darkest Chocolate Cake with Red Wine Glaze
items.caption: Finally, a sophisticated birthday cake for the grownups in the room, or anyone else who loves dark chocolate and red wine.

items.title: Carrot Cake with Cream Cheese-Lemon Zest Frosting
items.caption: With sweetness provided by pineapples and carrots beefing up the batter, this is a cake you can feel good about indulging in. It's made from fruits and vegetables, after all.

items.title: Persian Love Cake
items.caption: This rose-scented whipped cream filled cake takes birthday in an exotic direction, inspired by the aromatics found in Persian, Turkish, and Indian confections.

items.title: Lemon-Pistachio Crunch Cake
items.caption: You'll want to start prepping at least a day ahead to make this special-occasion cake‚Äîthe frosting base and lemon curd must chill overnight before using.

items.title: Spice Cake with Blackberry Filling and Cream Cheese Frosting
items.caption: Blackberries turn a familiar spice cake into a sophisticated finale for a birthday celebration.

items.title: Orange Layer Cake with Buttercream Frosting and Berries
items.caption: This is the perfect cake for anyone with a summer birthday. That's when berries are at their most delicious.

items.title: White Chocolate Truffle and Chocolate Fudge Layer Cake
items.caption: Think of this as truffles wrapped in truffles. White chocolate truffle separates the amaretto-brushed cake layers, and there's more truffle filling in the whipped cream icing.

items.title: Cider Spice Cake
items.caption: Apples and spice and everything nice! Try this cake for a fall birthday celebration.
